This is extremely well-documented. Here's a comprehensive answer:

---

## Universal Alternatives to Claude's Programmable Tool Calling

The industry has converged on **4 patterns**, usable across any AI IDE or model. Think of them as layers — you can use one or combine several.

---

### Pattern 1: Tool Selection in the Client (simplest)

Just **limit which tools are exposed** to the model per session. Every IDE (Cursor, Windsurf, etc.) supports enabling/disabling individual MCP tools.

**Tradeoff:** Manual, doesn't scale, can't dynamically change mid-session.

---

### Pattern 2: Composed / Virtual MCP Server (BFF pattern)

Build a **single MCP server** that internally orchestrates multiple tools and returns only the aggregated result to the model. The model calls one tool; your server calls 10 internally.

```typescript
// Your MCP server exposes ONE tool:
server.tool("get_unlinked_bugs", async () => {
  const bugs = await jiraClient.listIssues({ type: "Bug", status: "Open" });
  const prs  = await githubClient.listPRs({ state: "open" });

  const prKeys = prs.map(p => p.title.match(/[A-Z]+-\d+/)).flat().filter(Boolean);
  const unlinked = bugs.filter(b => !prKeys.includes(b.key));

  return { unlinked }; // Only this reaches the model context
});
```

This is the **Backend-for-Frontend (BFF) pattern** applied to MCP. IBM's [`mcp-composer`](https://ibm.github.io/mcp-composer/) automates this.

**Best for:** Known, predictable multi-step workflows.

---

### Pattern 3: MCP Code Mode Sandbox (closest to Claude's approach)

This is the **direct universal equivalent**. Expose only 2 tools to the model:

| Tool | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `search_tools` | Semantic search to discover available tools |
| `execute_code` | Run agent-generated code in a sandbox with all tools pre-wired as functions |

The model writes code that calls tools in a loop — raw responses stay inside the sandbox, only a small summary returns to context. **Cloudflare** (using V8 isolates), **StackOne**, and **Block** all implement this independently.

```typescript
// The agent generates and you execute this:
const bugs = await tools.jira_list_issues({ type: "Bug" });
const prs  = await tools.github_list_prs({ state: "open" });
const unlinked = bugs.filter(b => !prs.some(p => p.title.includes(b.key)));
return `${unlinked.length} bugs have no linked PR`;
// Only this string ↑ hits the model context. Raw data stayed in sandbox.
```

The sandbox runner bridges tool calls back to your real MCP server:

```javascript
// sandbox-runner.mjs
globalThis.tools = {};
for (const tool of toolDefs) {
  globalThis.tools[tool.name] = async (args) => {
    const res = await fetch(mcpBaseUrl, {
      method: "POST",
      body: JSON.stringify({ jsonrpc: "2.0", method: "tools/call",
        params: { name: tool.name, arguments: args } })
    });
    return (await res.json()).result;
  };
}
```

Measured results: **81–96% token reduction** vs direct tool calling (Cloudflare: 81%, StackOne: 96%).

**Works in:** Cursor, Windsurf, Gemini CLI, any MCP-compatible host — model-agnostic.

---

### Pattern 4: RAG-MCP / Dynamic Tool Discovery (scaling to 100s of tools)

Use **semantic search or BM25** to only inject the relevant tool definitions into context for a given prompt. Anthropic also ships this natively as `tool_search` in their API, but you can build it yourself as an MCP server.

```
User: "Find open Jira bugs"
  → Search tool index → returns only jira_list_issues definition
  → Only 1 tool definition enters context (not 50+)
```

Research shows this reduces tool-definition tokens by **50%+** and improves tool selection accuracy by **200%** on benchmarks.

---

### Which Pattern for Which Situation

| Scenario | Best Pattern |
|---|---|
| Simple, 1-2 tool calls | Pattern 1: just limit tools |
| Known multi-step workflow | Pattern 2: composed MCP server |
| Dynamic, data-heavy, cross-provider | Pattern 3: Code Mode sandbox |
| 50+ tools, discovery problem | Pattern 4: RAG-MCP |
| Production system | Pattern 3 + 4 combined |

---

**Bottom line:** Pattern 3 (Code Mode sandbox) is the universal, IDE-agnostic equivalent of Claude's programmable tool calling. It's model-agnostic, MCP-standard, and already proven at Cloudflare, Block, and StackOne — giving the same core benefits (no round-trips, raw data stays out of context) without depending on Anthropic's `code_execution_20260120` API feature.

